I find subs like this on r/investing tend to devolve into "hurr durr TSMC 5nm Intel sucks hurr du LiSa Su JiM kElLeR".

&amp;#x200B;

People don't realize there are possibly hundreds of process steps in the semiconductor manufacturing process, of which lithography is a few dozen.

&amp;#x200B;

A common line you'll see on Reddit is that "Intel doesn't innovate". [They have the 5th or 6th highest R&amp;D budget in the entire world](https://spendmenot.com/blog/top-rd-spenders/) despite being the smallest company in the top 10. Intel has its fingers in AI, ADAS, Photonics, Quantum Computing, fundamental chemical engineering and materials science research, etc.

&amp;#x200B;

Intel is a tremendous force of innovation, if you go to the top universities in the US, you'll see a ton of PhD. labs funded by Intel, you won't see any from AMD. Intel is doing fundamental, zero short term profit fundamental scientific research in a plethora of fields which AMD hasn't even heard of.

&amp;#x200B;

I'm not shitting on AMD - I think they are primed to eat away at Intel's market share in the short- medium term. I don't agree with shitting on Intel for the plethora of simpish reasons Reddit tends to do however. Intel has never gotten credit for anything it has ever done. It's like this is a permanently hated company. They could invent nuclear fusion tomorrow and someone will trot out their anti-trust activities from 1999 and shit on them to applause.

&gt;On top of that there is no capacity in TSMC for Intel (said TSMC).

&amp;#x200B;

No idea where you read that. MobilEye Q5 chips are being fabbed at TSMC 7nm FinFET as we speak.

&amp;#x200B;

I agree with the general gist of your comments.
